A call to SVGSCGElement.getWidth().getBaseVal().getValue() might result in a
NullpointerException if the svg looks something like this:

<svg  width="30pt" height="20.415pt" .... </svg>


Example program:
public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
    String DUMMY_SVG = "<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>\n"
        + "<!DOCTYPE svg PUBLIC '-//W3C//DTD SVG 1.0//EN'
'http://www.w3.org/TR/2001/REC-SVG-20010904/DTD/svg10.dtd'>\n"
        + "<svg xmlns:a='http://ns.adobe.com/AdobeSVGViewerExtensions/3.0/'\n"
        + "width='1pt' height='1pt' viewBox='0 0 1 1'/>";

    String parser = XMLResourceDescriptor.getXMLParserClassName();
    SAXSVGDocumentFactory documentFactory = new SAXSVGDocumentFactory(parser);
    SVGDocument doc = documentFactory.createSVGDocument(null, new
ByteArrayInputStream(DUMMY_SVG.getBytes()));

    SVGSVGElement root = doc.getRootElement();
    float width = root.getWidth().getBaseVal().getValue();
}

None of the SVG DOM can be used until the rendering tree has been
built.  The following code can do this for you:

        userAgent = new UserAgentAdapter();
        loader    = new DocumentLoader(userAgent);
        builder   = new GVTBuilder();
        svgDoc    = loader.loadDocument(uriStr, inputStream);

        ctx       = new BridgeContext(userAgent, loader);
        ctx.setDynamicState(BridgeContext.DYNAMIC);
        gvtRoot = builder.build(ctx, svgDoc);

